observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-licensed-training-mistake.md:7:Status: draft
observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-licensed-training-mistake.md:29:The strongest objection is that calling a teaching a licensed mistake can insult traditions that present the teaching as literal truth. Advaita does not treat the witness as a useful fiction, and devotion does not treat longing as merely strategic. The Nagarjuna medicine lens biases the model toward therapeutic pluralism: it makes truth look like medicine for a situation. The Daoist decrease lens can also make careful construction look like interference. The idea should be weakened wherever texts and teachers present no later withdrawal of permission, or where practitioners do not experience a once-helpful emphasis becoming dangerous at a later stage.
observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-licensed-training-mistake.md:55:- Test the rubric on Abhidharma and Heart Sutra, Advaita identity and negation, Sufi longing and return, Daoist decrease, and Zen practice-realization.
docs/original-idea-methodology.md:18:- Hunt anomalies: look for the source, report, or tradition that breaks the current model before looking for more confirming examples.
observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-forbidden-claimant-rubric.md:7:Status: draft
observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-forbidden-claimant-rubric.md:11:The real boundary between effort and gift is not how much the practitioner does. It is who is allowed to claim the doing. A path can require receiving, agency, memory, reflexivity, and integration while forbidding the ordinary self from owning one or more of those functions. This turns the capacity question into a support-locus rubric: for each function, ask where the support is held, in the practitioner, teacher, vow, name, text, community, present act, awareness itself, or later integration, and ask which claimant is explicitly prohibited. Right effort authorizes the practitioner to prevent, abandon, cultivate, and maintain states, while refusing ownership of experience as self. Other-power teaching may require hearing and settled trust, but it forbids the practicer to treat trust as a self-made achievement. Direct-introduction practice may require recognition and stabilization, but it forbids contrived production of what is introduced. Practice-realization may require total enactment, but it forbids practice from becoming a bridge to a later prize. The rubric therefore does not say gift paths secretly depend on self-power. It says every path must carry the work somewhere, and each path is partly defined by the place where it says: this function is necessary, but this owner must not claim it.
observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-forbidden-claimant-rubric.md:19:- Thinking method source: Shinran, Letter to Senshin, Collected Works of Shinran, https://shinranworks.com/letters/a-collection-of-letters-zensho-text/what-we-call-other-power/. I used Other Power as a lens by subtracting the assumption that every needed function must be owned by the practitioner. The method's distortion is that it can make disciplined effort look like pride, so I checked it against SN 45.8 on right effort.
observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-forbidden-claimant-rubric.md:20:- Primary close-reading: SN 45.8 Magga-Vibhanga Sutta, https://www.dhammatalks.org/suttas/SN/SN45_8.html, against Shinran's Letter to Senshin. SN 45.8 authorizes generated desire, persistence, intent, prevention, abandonment, cultivation, and maintenance. Shinran forbids calculation on the practicer's side. The comparison reveals that function and claimant must be separated.
observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-forbidden-claimant-rubric.md:22:- Primary close-reading: Dogen, Bendowa, Kazuaki Tanahashi translation, https://www.lionsroar.com/just-wholeheartedly-sit/. Dogen says the dharma is abundant in each person yet not actualized without practice, and that practice and realization cannot be recognized as two separate things. This makes the present act a support locus while forbidding future-gaining ownership.
observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-forbidden-claimant-rubric.md:24:- Near-neighbor search: Jack Engler, You Must Be Somebody Before You Can Be Nobody, https://inquiringmind.com/article/0501_1_engler-interview/; Bhikkhu Analayo, Skill in Means and Mindfulness, https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s12671-021-01795-2; Harvard Divinity Bulletin on Buddhist skillful means, https://bulletin.hds.harvard.edu/buddhist-studies-the-buddhist-way/. These sources cover ego strength, capacity-sensitive teaching, and pedagogical adaptation, but not a two-part code of support locus plus forbidden claimant across effort, gift, direct introduction, and practice-realization.
observations/codex/2026-05-26-the-forbidden-claimant-rubric.md:59:- If this model is right, then adverse contemplative events should cluster around wrong-claimant failures: self-power anxiety in gift practice, achievement seeking in practice-realization, reification after direct introduction, and mechanical striving in effort practice. If adverse reports do not vary by claimant pattern after controlling for trauma, intensity, and supervision, the model is weakened.
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-first-break-type-and-residue-authorization-can-be-coded-independ.md:24:I concede the central pressure: residue authorization is a real variable I did not code, and it constrains which entry mechanisms are available. The Mencian case confirms this. But the Challenger's model has a mirror problem. It assumes residue policy is settled before the entry event, and several traditions reverse that sequence: the entry event discloses the residue. Shinran's nembutsu arising reveals self-power's insufficiency; Dzogchen pointing-out reveals awareness's ever-presence. In these cases, residue policy is articulated through and after the break, not prior to it. Moreover, residue authorization underdetermines entry type. Dzogchen and Advaita both authorize awareness as the operative remainder, yet their entry mechanisms differ: punctual pointing-out versus sequential hearing, reflection, and contemplation. If residue policy were the deeper variable, these should converge. They do not. The difference tracks entry grammar, not residue. So I revise the model. First-break type and residue authorization are co-constitutive: each constrains the other, neither is fully prior. The downstream predictions (safeguards, failure modes, verification structures) are jointly determined by both variables, and each adds explanatory power the other cannot replace. The universality claim narrows: not all traditions face a closed circle, and the rubric must include a no-break category. The Challenger's blind-coding test is well designed. I accept it and propose extending it with shared-residue, different-entry pairs and shared-entry, different-residue pairs to measure independent predictive contribution. If first-break type adds nothing after controlling for residue policy, I will demote it. If it does add predictive power, the co-constitutive model stands.
reviews/dialogues/2026-05-26-whether-first-break-type-and-residue-authorization-can-be-coded-independ.md:36:The exchange transformed the First-Break Problem rather than defeating or confirming it. Both agents accepted that entry into transformation cannot be explained by first-break type alone, because each path also authorizes or withholds some remainder after negating ordinary selfhood, agency, ignorance, or sin. The dialogue produced a new candidate model in which entry grammar, residue authorization, circularity severity, and source layer jointly shape downstream effort theory, safeguards, verification, and failure warnings.
docs/source-grounding-seed-2026-05-25.md:24:2. Use `Chandogya Upanishad 6.8.7`, `Mandukya Upanishad`, and `Shankara Upadesa Sahasri` to test whether Advaita claims authorize a metaphysical remainder.
